Visualization of my collected observation data

Frequency & Sender Type of SNS Messages

Introduction: About the data

As a continuation from Project 2, I have reused the same survey to log this projects observation. This is a personal survey with the intent to analyse my personal activity on SNS based on the frequency of interaction. This is done by recording the number of SNS messages received during different time frames of the day:

  • morning: 2:00am - 9:59am
  • midday: 10:00am - 17:59pm
  • night: 18:00pm - 1:59am

and categorizing sender into two groups, friends & acquaintances and family & partner.

As I was the source for the responses logged in this survey in the previous projects, this new batch of observation will also be done by myself only.

Plot 1

First we will take a look at the social activity difference between the last time observations were logged, and this lastest recent observations.

While the recent observation session has a higher median of messages received in a day, we cannot conclude with confidence that this month was more social in comparison as there isnt a significant difference between the 2 sessions. It is also notable that there was a day with 24 messages received in the old session.

Plot 2

Above is a graph visualizing the number of days observing each category of interaction: whether there was message interaction with both friends and family, only friends, only family or no interaction at all.

Understandably in my case, friends & acquaintances have a higher frequency of interaction via SNS messages. This is because some of my friends live oversea, which means we have limited options when it comes to communication, and that likely contributed strongly to the skewness seen on the graph.

Plot 3

Above is a graph visualizing the average volume of SNS messages received, categorized by their sender group, across the three time frames defined in the introduction.

I rarely have any social interaction in the morning time frame, and that is to be expected. I live in the same place as my family and my friends are just starting their day, there is rarely the need for social interaction.

Then comes midday, this time frame is notably the only time frame where I trade messages with my family. This reflects the numerous moment of need for communication while I am at the university and they are at work. Similarly there is an increase of interaction from friends too, that is to be expected on a regular day at the university.

The most of my free time, and reasonably everyone elses, are during the night, which is when I get to catch up with my friends and communicate online. No family SNS messages received here because everyone is already at home.
